## Setup & Deployment

Two deployment modes. Choose based on your use case:

| | Local | Service |
|---|---|---|
| **Board storage** | `.task-board/` directory in project | board-server (bbolt + MinIO) |
| **Multi-agent** | Single agent at a time | Multiple agents concurrently |
| **Persistence** | Git (committed with project) | Server-side (backed up separately) |
| **Network** | None | HTTP (LAN or remote) |
| **Setup time** | Zero — just use CLI | 2 min (make) or 5 min (Docker) |
| **Best for** | Solo dev, small projects | Teams, swarm agents, persistent boards |

### Local mode (default)

No board bootstrap needed. CLI creates `.task-board/` on first `create` command.
If you run setup/install scripts, profile configs are created automatically:

```bash
# Canonical workstation setup for CLI/TUI + installed skill artifact
./scripts/setup.sh --mode local --board-dir .task-board

# Start using
task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=my-feature, description="...")'
task-board q --format compact 'summary()'
```

Board lives in `.task-board/` inside your project. Commit it to git for persistence.

If this board lives inside a real code repository that agents will work on, bootstrap it from the `skill-project-management` source checkout with repo-local agents enabled:

```bash
cd /path/to/skill-project-management
./scripts/setup.sh --project-dir /path/to/project --mode local --board-dir .task-board --bootstrap-local-agents
```

This is the expected companion step for board setup in a project repo:
- `.agents/` gets the local runtime contents and templates
- `.claude/` and `.codex/` are refreshed as thin links into `.agents/`
- spawned agents can reliably see repo-local instructions instead of only global installs
- agents can call `task-board q 'project_config()'` before work to verify whether this repo uses a local board or a remote profile

### Service mode (board-server)

#### Quick start (local binary)

```bash
# Install CLI/TUI + project profile via the canonical setup path
./scripts/setup.sh --mode remote --remote-url http://localhost:8080 --remote-user sampleuser --remote-board my-project

# If this board drives work in a code repo, prefer the single setup command with repo-local agents
./scripts/setup.sh --project-dir /path/to/project --mode remote --remote-url http://localhost:8080 --remote-board my-project --bootstrap-local-agents

# Build board-server binary (binary-only helper)
make install-backend

# Start server locally
board-server --addr :8080 --data-dir ./data/boards --auth-db ./data/auth.db
```

Server prints everything you need on startup:
```
  board-server running:
  URL:         http://localhost:8080
  Data:        ./data/boards

  FIRST RUN — admin token (save it, shown once):
  tb_xxxxx

  Quick start:
    export TASK_BOARD_REMOTE=http://localhost:8080
    export TASK_BOARD_ID=<board-id>
```

Select a user, store the token in Keychain, then go:
```bash
export TASK_BOARD_REMOTE=http://localhost:8080
export TASK_BOARD_USER=sampleuser

# Create a board
task-board admin board create my-project "My Project"

export TASK_BOARD_ID=my-project
task-board login sampleuser tb_xxxxx

# Use normally — all DSL commands route to server
task-board q --format compact 'summary()'
task-board m 'create(type=epic, name=auth-system)'

# Optional: write remote profile config explicitly
./scripts/setup.sh --mode remote --remote-url http://localhost:8080 --remote-user sampleuser --remote-board my-project
```

#### Docker deployment (production)

Full stack: Caddy (TLS reverse proxy) + board-server + MinIO (resource storage).

```bash
cd tools/board-server/deploy
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env: set BOARD_DOMAIN, MinIO credentials

./deploy.sh         # Build + start (prints admin token on first run)
./status.sh         # Check health
./logs.sh           # Tail logs
./backup.sh         # Backup data
./stop.sh           # Stop all
./e2e-test.sh       # End-to-end test
```

For self-signed TLS (localhost/LAN):
```bash
# CLI flag
task-board --insecure q --format compact 'summary()'

# Or environment (inherited by spawned agents)
export TASK_BOARD_TLS_NO_VERIFY=1

# Or unified config file (project-local)
# ./task-board.config.json  (NOTE: no token here — use 'task-board login')
{
  "mode":"remote",
  "local":{"board_dir":".task-board"},
  "spawn":{"max_parallel":20},
  "remote":{"url":"https://board.local","board":"my-project","tls_no_verify":true}
}
```

#### User management (service mode)

```bash
# Create user + token
task-board admin user create alice
task-board admin token create alice

# Grant board access
task-board admin access grant alice my-project editor

# List users
task-board admin user list
```

Roles: `admin` (full access), `editor` (read/write board), `viewer` (read-only).

### Makefile reference

These targets are build helpers. They are not a replacement for `./scripts/setup.sh` when you need the installed skill copy, role sync, or self-update metadata.

```bash
make                    # install-frontend (CLI + TUI)
make install-frontend   # CLI + TUI — developer workstation
make install-backend    # CLI + server — deployment
make install            # all three binaries
make test               # run all tests
make snapshot           # goreleaser snapshot (cross-platform build)
make clean              # remove binaries + dist/
```

